data: {"type":"response.output_text.done","content_index":0,"item_id":"msg_0dec2cf2d12bf97700699fc99a23fc81968648cd82a6e8bbc7","logprobs":[],"output_index":1,"sequence_number":156,"text":"**Foundry Agent Service** is Microsoft’s managed runtime in **Microsoft Foundry (Azure AI Foundry)** for building, deploying, and operating **production-ready AI agents** (not just chatbots). It stitches together the key pieces you need to run agents safely and at scale: models, tools, conversation state, orchestration, safety controls, identity/network integration, and observability. ([learn.microsoft.com](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/ai-foundry/agents/overview?view=foundry-classic))\n\n### What it does (core capabilities)\n- **Runs an “agent” end-to-end**: manages conversations/threads, executes “runs,” and orchestrates tool calls so the agent can take actions or fetch data. ([learn.microsoft.com](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/ai-foundry/agents/overview?view=foundry-classic))  \n- **Tool orchestration**: lets the model decide when to call configured tools (and with which inputs), then incorporates tool outputs back into the response/workflow. ([learn.microsoft.com](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/ai-foundry/agents/how-to/tools-classic/overview?view=foundry-classic))  \n- **Trust & governance building blocks**: designed to support policy enforcement, content safety, and production operations so you can move beyond demos into real workflows. ([learn.microsoft.com](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/ai-foundry/agents/overview?view=foundry-classic))  \n\n### Tools you can plug into agents\nFoundry Agent Service supports a catalog of tools that broadly fall into:\n\n**Knowledge tools (grounding / retrieval)** to bring in context from:\n- **Azure AI Search**, **File Search**, **Microsoft Fabric**, etc. ([learn.microsoft.com](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/ai-foundry/agents/how-to/tools-classic/overview?view=foundry-classic))  \n- Public web via **Grounding with Bing Search** (real-time web grounding). ([learn.microsoft.com](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/ai-foundry/agents/how-to/tools-classic/bing-grounding?view=foundry-classic))  \n- Domain-limited web via **Bing Custom Search** (search only approved domains/subdomains). ([learn.microsoft.com](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/ai-foundry/agents/how-to/tools-classic/bing-custom-search?view=foundry-classic))  \n\n**Action tools (do things)** such as:\n- **Azure Logic Apps** (workflow automation),\n- **OpenAPI** / **MCP** connectors,\n- **function calling / Azure Functions**,\n- and other action-oriented capabilities listed in the tool overview. ([learn.microsoft.com](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/ai-foundry/agents/how-to/tools-classic/overview?view=foundry-classic))  \n\n### When you’d use it\nTypical use cases are “work” automations like summarizing documents, processing invoices, handling support tickets, or publishing content—where you want an agent that can **reason + retrieve + act** with operational controls. ([learn.microsoft.com](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/ai-foundry/agents/overview?view=foundry-classic))\n\n### Quick clarification (so I describe the right thing)\nWhen you say “Foundry Agent Service,” do you mean **Microsoft Foundry / Azure AI Foundry Agents**, or a different product named “Foundry” (e.g., Palantir Foundry)? If you tell me which one (and whether you’re using the *new* or *classic* Foundry portal), I can outline the exact APIs, architecture, and a minimal “first agent” setup."}

